d anti-Semitism prevention programs specifically tailored for Muslim immigrants and refugees, so that they, too, can learn the lessons of the Holocaust and embrace Germany's most important postwar democratic political values. Based on ethnographic research conducted over a decade, Subcontractors of Guilt explores when, how, and why Muslim Germans have moved to the center of Holocaust memory discussions. Esra Özyürek argues that German society "subcontracts" guilt of the Holocaust to new minority immigrant arrivals, with the false promise of this process leading to inclusion into the German social contract and equality with other members of postwar German society. By focusing on the recently formed but already sizable sector of Muslim-only anti-Semitism and Holocaust education programs, this book explores the paradoxes of postwar German national identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAntisemitismxStudy and teachingzGermany. 0aAntisemitismzGermanyxPrevention. 0aCollective memoryzGermany. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xStudy and teachingzGermany. 0aMuslimsxEducationzGermany. 0aMuslimszGermanyxAttitudes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAuschwitz.  aHolocaust memory.  aMuslim minority.  aantisemitism.  ademocratization.  aemotions.  agender.  aguilt.  amigration.  avictimhood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363557940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503635579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503635579/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles